    <Descriptive_Notes>
      <Descriptive_Note>
        <Note_Text>Xylophones consisting of large wood keys or slabs resting across banana tree trunks, or a combination of straw bundles and banana tree trunks, found in many parts of sub-Saharan Africa. Commonly from two to six players interlock different melodic patterns on a single instrument.</Note_Text>
        <Note_Language>English</Note_Language>
        <Note_Contributors>
          <Note_Contributor>
            <Contributor_id>10000000/VP</Contributor_id>
          </Note_Contributor>
        </Note_Contributors>
        <Note_Sources>
          <Note_Source>
            <Source>
              <Source_ID>2000030041/Sadie, New Grove Dictionary of Musical Instruments (1984)</Source_ID>
            </Source>
          </Note_Source>
        </Note_Sources>
      </Descriptive_Note>
      <Descriptive_Note>
        <Note_Text>Xilófonos que consisten en llaves de madera o tablillas que descansan sobre troncos de árbol bananero cruzándolos, o sobre una combinación de éstos con fardos de paja, encontrándose en muchas partes del Africa subsahariana. Comúnmente de dos a seis ejecutantes entrelazan diferentes motivos melódicos en un solo instrumento.</Note_Text>
        <Note_Language>Spanish</Note_Language>
        <Note_Contributors>
          <Note_Contributor>
            <Contributor_id>10000131/CDBP-SNPC</Contributor_id>
          </Note_Contributor>
        </Note_Contributors>
        <Note_Sources>
          <Note_Source>
            <Source>
              <Source_ID>2000051034/TAA database (2000-)</Source_ID>
            </Source>
          </Note_Source>
        </Note_Sources>
      </Descriptive_Note>
      <Descriptive_Note>
        <Note_Text>Xylofoons bestaande uit grote houten toetsen die overdwars op de boomstam liggen, of op een combinatie van rietschoven en boomstammen; oorspronkelijk ontwikkeld en bespeeld in sub-saharisch Afrika.</Note_Text>
        <Note_Language>Dutch</Note_Language>
        <Note_Contributors>
          <Note_Contributor>
            <Contributor_id>10000205/AAT-Ned</Contributor_id>
          </Note_Contributor>
        </Note_Contributors>
        <Note_Sources>
          <Note_Source>
            <Source>
              <Source_ID>2000113770/AAT-Ned (1994-)</Source_ID>
            </Source>
          </Note_Source>
          <Note_Source>
            <Source>
              <Source_ID>2000052452/Encyclopedie van muziekinstrumenten (1977)</Source_ID>
            </Source>
          </Note_Source>
        </Note_Sources>
      </Descriptive_Note>
      <Descriptive_Note>
        <Note_Text>由大型木鍵或木片所組成的木琴，木鍵或木片橫置於香蕉樹樹幹，或稻草束和香蕉樹樹幹的混合物上，非洲撒哈拉沙漠以南許多地方皆可見其蹤跡，通常由2至6位演奏者，在同一架原木木琴上以不同旋律模式聯合演奏。
</Note_Text>
        <Note_Language>Chinese (traditional)</Note_Language>
        <Note_Contributors>
          <Note_Contributor>
            <Contributor_id>10000250/AS-Academia Sinica</Contributor_id>
          </Note_Contributor>
        </Note_Contributors>
      </Descriptive_Note>
      <Descriptive_Note>
        <Note_Text>Xylofon, das aus großen Klanghölzern oder Holzplatten besteht, die auf Bananenstämmen oder einer Kombination aus Stroh und Bananenstämmen ruhen; es ist in vielen Teilen von Subsahara-Afrika zu anzutreffen. Gewöhnlich verweben zwischen zwei und sechs Spieler verschiedene Melodiemuster auf einem einzigen Instrument.</Note_Text>
        <Note_Language>German</Note_Language>
        <Note_Contributors>
          <Note_Contributor>
            <Contributor_id>10000232/IfM-SMB-PK</Contributor_id>
          </Note_Contributor>
        </Note_Contributors>
        <Note_Sources>
          <Note_Source>
            <Source>
              <Source_ID>2000122134/IfM Berlin</Source_ID>
            </Source>
          </Note_Source>
        </Note_Sources>
      </Descriptive_Note>
    </Descriptive_Notes>
